title: Block or Brick Power Supply Adapter Mounting Bracket

description.text:
The openSCAD script provides a configurable mounting bracket for use with the rectangular brick or block style power adapters or power supplies often used with laptops and other small electronics.

The bracket can be prepared so that the power adapter is mounted in a lay-flat configuration, or in an upright, on-edge configuration. A top-level geometry section of the script allows the user to specify the desired openSCAD result. Two components are provided. One serves as a wrap-around for the power adapter, and the second component serves as a base.

The wrap component can be configured with a closed bottom and used alone for a low-profile mount. Configuring the wrap component with an "open" bottom allows it to be "sprung" over a cabled power adapter. Here, use of the base component can be used to help stabilize the open-bottom wrap component when mounting the adapter. The base component also increases the gap available for convection airflow cooling between the power adapter and the mounting surface.

A sample STL file has provided for mounting a 55mm x 34mm power adapter in a lay-flat orientation. The intent is for the openSCAD source to be tailored for your application rather than using this specific STL file. Two brackets would typically be used to mount an adapter.

This is a remix of my Inateck FE3001 Hard Disk Drive Enclosure Mounting Bracket available at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2662310. Adaptation consists of changing the size parameters and applying a different method to form the wrap component.

description.text:
UPDATE: See below...

The Monoprice Select Mini V2 comes with a cloned V6-style hot end.
If you put a genuine e3d V6 hot end and nozzle in the stock mount, you find yourself a good 5mm away from the bed to normal.

There are many ways around this and many other prints to help overcome the gap.
But I decided to make one simple piece to mount the genuine e3d V6 which uses all the rest of the stock front part and fan. No spacers etc. needed.

I modelled the original back part of the mount, then lowered it 5mm and reduced the material a bit to make things printable without supports.

Best printed in ABS. Though you could probably get away with PETG. Up to a point ;) (see UPDATE below)

This is my first attempt at using Fusion 360. Thanks to all the helpful YouTube videos out there! ;)

Also included is the model I made of the stock mount with everything in the original position. Feel free to chop it up and do what you like with it.

UPDATE (17 Dec 17): OK. So I've updated the design on this a little and got rid of the bottom half of the 'ring around the heat sink. No need for it. And it can be prone to melting.

Also, I decided that 5mm was a bit too low, so reduced the amount down from stock to 3mm. This saves having to crush the bed down too much.

description.text:
THE TALE OF THE LITTLE 3D PRINTER THAT SAVED CHRISTMAS !!!!

My wife loves making Christmas cookies. While using her decorative cookie press, the poorly conceived contraption wrecked itself when the sharp metal end of the push arm cut through the plastic plunger. Sadness darkened her festive and cheery mood because now her colorful and pretty cookies couldn't get made.

Being a loving and dutiful husband, who is always looking for a reason to 3D print anything, I assessed the likely engineered short comings of the cookie press. Knowing I could do better than the devious disastrous designer who made the cookie press, I dashed off to the hardware store and bought a 20 cent stainless steel washer. I quickly pranced back home and fired up the CAD software. I engineered the new plunger with the washer embedded so the push arm would not cut through the plastic when the cookies got pressed. An hour of hot molten plastic later, and the press was pressing cookies once again !

Hallelujah !!!! Christmas has been saved by 3D Printing. And the little Christmas Elf Shawna was merrily making cookies once again...

description.text:
This ancient game is probably a direct ancestor of the better known Nine Men's Morris as well as Tic-Tac-Toe. It is played on a board of three rows and three columns. Players have three pieces each and take turns first placing then moving their pieces. The goal is to form a straight or diagonal line of three. There are two forms of the game: In the simple version, diagonal moves are illegal; in the more complex variant they are allowed.

"Six Men's Morris is played in the same way as Nine Men's Morris, with two changes, the first is that each player has six men and the second is that it is played on [a modified] board (which is similar to that used by Nine Men's Morris, except it lacks the outer set of lines)."

Variation: Five Men's Morris is played on the same modified board, but using 5 men on a side instead of six.

This is an 8-bit Mario (as in Super Mario Bros.) hanging ornament made specifically for multi-extruder printers (though I have included a one-piece model for single-extruder machines). It's perfect for the rear-view mirror, Christmas tree, etc.

Please be aware that - though some post-printing assembly is required - the fully colourized version of this model was not designed to be printed in pieces on a single-extruder machine and assembled afterwards. Use mario_onepiece.stl to get everything at once in a single colour.

The print in the cover photo was done on a quad extruder Prusa i3 MK2 MMU as follows:

Step 1:

  • mario_step1_white.stl white PLA (extruder 1)
  • mario_step1_green.stl green PLA (extruder 2)
  • mario_step1_red.stl red PLA (extruder 3)

Step 2:

  • mario_step2_blue.stl blue PLA (extruder 1)
  • mario_step2_brown.stl brown PLA (extruder 2)
  • mario_step2_red.stl red PLA (extruder 3)
  • mario_step2_flesh.stl pale flesh PLA (extruder 4)

Step 3:

  • mario_step3_black.stl black PLA (extruder 1)

Step 4:

  • mario_step4_yellow.stl gold PLA (extruder 4)

Assembly:
Because I used more colours than I have extruders, some post-printing assembly is required. I have allowed for some wiggle room between the various parts, so things should fit together fairly easily with little-to-no sanding/clean-up. In general, the yellow/gold buttons and black eye/stache get attached to the Mario model, which then gets placed into the Mario-shaped hole in the white backplate.

For those of you who have fewer extruders (or who like painting a lot more than I do), I have included mario_onepiece.stl, which can be used to print everything at once in a single colour/material, no post-printing assembly required.

When printed at 100% size, the ornament measures approximately 57mm x 75mm.

description.text:
I made the original three switch design for my son who loves gears. It's worked fine for the past 3 months so I made a single light switch plate for my basement light switch.

I printed the whole thing out in 14 hours at one time in gray PLA. I used 20% infill which worked but didn't have the best surface finish. (the all gray picture above) In later runs I used 40% and that worked much better.

I didn't like the prison look for the light switch so I remade the gear and pinion using orange PET-G.

I noticed that the gears run smoother with the orange PET-G. So that's interesting. . . .

Notes:

The small gear and crank do not need to be glued together but I did anyway.

The crank and gear are held onto the light switch plate by an m3 screw. I sized the hole in the post so that it does not need to be drilled out. It does need to be tapped with an m3 tap.

Tap that hole

After you print this out and remove the supports. The post on the light switch plate needs to be threaded with an m3 tap.

The Pinion has to be in the groove before you put it on the wall. The holes in the bottom of the pinions are so you can sneak the bottom screw into the light switch.

If it gets jammed you might not have tightened down the screw enough.

Installation::
Break all support off parts, sand the back of gears with 200 grit sandpaper for smooth operation

Glue the small gear to the handle using loctite 401 using the nubs as guides

Tap all the post holes with the M3 tap set

Before installation, tighten all gears onto light switch plate and check the back to make sure the bolt doesn't go all the way through.

!!!(IF THE BOLTS PROTRUDE OUT THE BACK OF THE LIGHT SWITCH; IT IS AN ELECTROCUTION HAZARD)!!!

Put a piece of electrical tape over the back of the post holes.

Make sure light switch gears operate smoothly. (I had to sand down the side of the pinion for smooth operation.)

Disassemble everything.

Turn OFF power to the light switch, at the residences' circuit breaker.

Mount light switch plate to the wall with the pinion part pre-installed.

Mount gears to light switch plate.

Test for smooth operation, You may need to sand the gear teeth or sides of the pinion if the print was rough or stringy.

Turn power house power back ON at the breaker.

description.text: This is a Ketran, an alien from the Animorphs books series (copyright Scholastic and KA Applegate). Big thanks to YahooJapan, for their extensive database of models that I drew upon for parts to combine in Meshmixer, in order to make the various Animorphs aliens.

The pictures at the end, are of my version 1, but the basic idea is there... I will try and take some better pictures tomorrow!

I made this when my 'stock' carriage broke, and I wanted something stronger, and more durable. Then, I got looking into it, and decided to incorporate a fan duct when I couldn't find anything to just "add on" to it... so, with that being said, you should print the fan duct as well. It works VERY well, and I have had to set my fan speeds down to 65% speed.

This was designed for my V6 clone, which raises the bed about 15mm higher than stock, which I am using mirror to print on, so really it was closer to 20mm higher. This will work for the stock V5 nozzle, and is fully adjustable fan duct height, which should accommodate the volcano nozzle, on the V5 or the V6 head.

I have updated 3 versions of the carriage, to accommodate the 18mm barrel sensor, 12mm barrel sensor, and the bltouch. There is also an adaptor for the bltouch carriage, to mount the typical style resistance sensor.

The stock microswitch for the x endstop is also there, and works great!

The belt tensioner is a wedge style, which holds the belt securely, and you can also tighten it down much easier and better.

All parts I have designed and I have printed all except the the 2 barrel carriages, since I have the bltouch sensor.

If there are any modifications, or additional things you'd like me to add for you, please let me know!

and hey, if you like it... feel free to buy my a coffee :D (send me a "tip")

Mounting and Securing everything

I am using the stock linear bearing mounts, with the M4 screws, and the square M4 nuts that came with my printer, and they fit perfectly between the rails.

I also use the M4 screw, and square nut for the nozzle mounts.

I use M3 screws and nuts to hold on the fan duct, and secure the belt tensioner.

the stock screw/nut for the microswitch also is reused to hold it secure as well.

originally was going to be a remix but wound up making it from scratch

this started as a quest to find a unsupported angle benchmark that suited me.

i found this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:419860 but it was unlabeled.
and then i saw it had a remix with labels (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2017348) but they were on the teeth. which i did not like.

so i imported the original into tinkercad, and saw the base that was really jaggedy. like the dev merged a bunch of rectangles without worrying about them being the same size or aligned.

so i made it from scratch
this one has the following specs
the teeth are 5 mm wide, 2 mm tall, and 15 mm long (before any merging)
the label base was 13 mm wide (before merging) and 2 mm tall and includes a 1 mm space between each tooth.
as i said earlier each space is 1 millimeter tall and can act as a fault line so you can break away any teeth you don't want to keep.
also the text extends 1 mm above the top of the base
i also made smaller sizes with the same specs as above. but with fewer teeth.

the small ones are made for those who have issues with larger models, have a small printer or just want to test a few sizes.
they have a size range as follows
width: 16.81 - 26 mm
depth: 17 or 29,
height: 7.93 - 15.2 mm
so they should fit on most tiny beds

i also made one that includes 0 and 90 degrees for those who want to print a full range of angles (between 0 and 90)

There are many fine filament reel holders here on Thingiverse, but I have noticed the lack of a simple, portable reel-to-reel winding rig setup. In the world of movie post production which I once haunted (though no fan of moviedom myself), we had access to workbench mounted, side loading film-winding rigs which let us easily wind through a reel of movie film (hundreds of feet long) to examine, clean or just prep the film for some process.

Herein I begin to help you have the same capability in the 3d filament world. You may "untangle," measure or even clean a roll of filament easily by building two of the item in the photos above.

Procedure is simple: get a 12" wood working clamp (crazy cheap at Harbor Freight) and cut off 4" from the open end. Next, jam 3" of 1/2" pvc pipe on the newly cut end, and push a 90 degree L piece on to that. Add a pvc pipe 3/34" long and an end cap.

It can now be clamped to the edge of any available table or appropriate piece of furniture.

For true stability, I add the extra footing of an Irwin Wide Bar Pad (from Lowes) to the top pad of the clamp. The bottom is fine without it.

Viola! A side-loading, portable and manual reel winding rig. All for around $10 each.

The only thing missing is a truly useful, universal fit handle. I don't know what the makers out there are using... maybe a small screw driver pushed in the filament end-saving hole along the rim?

I have an idea for the handle, but it will be a somewhat complicated build. Once I settle on the design my daughter has requested to offer them on Etsy. They must attach universally, firmly, and not un-screw as the reel is rotated.

Also included is an .stl file with some "souce" (arrow) and "target" (circle) tags to identify your winders, in case you have to step away or someone else has to resume your winding job. That way you always know what direction things were going!

Just open the clamp all the way, then slide the tag up into the partly-open bottom end of the vertical pvc tube.

description.text:
Anemone BC Remote Tentacle is a 3D printable case for BigClown Remote Station.

It is part of the open and free #anemoneCloud Platform, but it can be used completely standalone as well.

When used inside the Anemone Platform the Tentacle could be used as a DYI Open Hardware device which can be easily connected to cloud APIs, mobile app and/or other tentacles of open hardware devices. All this completely free of any charge. More documentation about how to use this Tentacle in the Anemone Ecosystem can be found at: Anemone Docs.

When used outside the Anemone Platform it can be used as a cute case for your BigClown Remote Station - the BigClown Remote Station can be assembled from the following BigClown modules:

  • The Core Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/core-module/
  • The Tag Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/tag-module/
  • The The Battery Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/battery-module/
  • 4x The AAA battery

You can add up to three BigClown Tags to measure stuff and plug two of them in to the Power Module and the third one can be plugged into the Core Module.

I am not the sole author of this thing or of the Anemone Project. Anemone Tentacle has been created as a team effort of our great team at Juicymo and our client. See more info about who is behind this here.

Tentacle Visualization can be found at YouTube

Anemone BC Remote Tentacle case is LEGO compatible!

  • The Walls (Anemone_BC_Remote_Case.stl)
  • The Top Cover (Anemone_BC_Remote_Top.stl)
  • The Top Buttons (Anemone_BC_Remote_Buttons.stl)

Or as a ready-to-print .stl file with all components (to be printed all at once):

In addition to the .stl ready-to-print file you can download a exported gcode file for the Prusa i3 MK2 3D Printer with ABS filament setting. We have used this gcode file to print our version of Anemone BC Base Tentacle on Kanárek (Prusa i3 MK2S Original 3D Printer).

Recommended print settings

The Anemone Tentacle case is optimized to be printed in ABS (but we have tested printing with PLA too and it works well).

We have used the open source Prusa Slic3r for slicing the .stl files into .gcode. The Prusa Slic3r has few advantages compared to the original Slic3r (like better supports and more).

Anemone Tentacle case looks awesome even on low print settings - which looks nice with a semi-transparent filament.

After printing the second and third parts (The Walls & The Top Cover) need to be cleaned of supports.

When done you can assemble the Anemone BC Remote Tentacle case.

The Anemone IoT Platform Story

The original idea for Anemone was to create a simple Open Hardware device which would be able to send information to the cloud (or internet) and which will be very easy to use for others.

Over time, the idea expanded a little. And we have ended up creating not just the Open Hardware device itself (we call it a Tentacle) but 3D printable case, cloud web application and even mobile application for iOS and Android as well.

And now we in fact have quite a nice ecosystem. Not with many apps right now, but it is ready to use! And that is where we need your help ;)

With Anemone, you can create a cloud enabled IoT apps in a very easy way and get them hosted for free in the Anemone Cloud. Or you can just print the Tentacle Case and upload a picture of it to the I made it section. Our Anemone BC Base Tentacle case is the very first 3D printed case for the BigClown Base Station Module.

And you can use it freely even completely outside the Anemone platform too.

So enjoy! ;)

I am not the sole author of this thing or of the Anemone Project. Anemone Tentacle has been created as a team effort of our great team at Juicymo and our client. See more info about who is behind this here.

description.text:
Designed as i have watched (youtube) that this quad suffers with with the rear dropping out when banking in tight turns. I thought a good part of this is from the rear props pushing down on the rear frame work.

The middle fin section has a runner through the middle/bottom that allows the battery cable to go through allowing the sides to be smooth to help with air flow.

I have yet to have the skill to fully test this design for dropout.

I printed in PLA with 2 skins and 10% infill.
The top plate could be printed with 100% to make it stronger with out to much weight increase.

The hole in the middle fin is to secure the battery cable with a cable tie.

The sections are glued together with super glue.

I haven't tried fitting the camera yet but the hole spacing is correct for the original camera to fit.

Das ist eine Zusammenstellung, um 4 Filamentrollen (in meinem Fall 3 1kg und 1 750g) in einer Samla Box von Ikea zu verstauen inklusive Bauanleitung.

I. Material

Man benötigt:

  • die 22l Version der Ikea Samla Box mit Deckel
  • ein PVC Rohr mit 32mm durchmesser aus dem Baumarkt
  • 4 Stück PTFE Röhrchen (4mm außen, 2mm innen) ca. 5cm lang
  • 6 Stück M4x10mm Schrauben und Muttern
  • 6 Stück M3x10mm Schrauben, optional 10 Stück
  • 8 Stück Kugellager 5x16x5, optional 16 Stück

II. Gedruckte Teil
Siehe Bild 1 & 2

III. Die einfache Variante

Du druckst dir nur "Spool_Guide und Spool_Holder_remix" aus und nutzt die Originalhalterung deines CR-10. Keine Sorge, auch mit eingeschraubter M3x10mm Schraube schleift nichts. (Bilder 12-14)

IV. Samla Komplett (gelbe und grüne Zahlen)

V. Die Vorbereitung (gelbe Zahlen)

  1. Anzeichnen der späteren Auslässe.
  2. 15mm Löcher bohren üfr die Auslässe
  3. Anzeichnen des ersten Loches der Rohrhalterung
  4. Das erste Loch Bohren und die Halterung als Schablone für die anderen beiden Löcher nutzen.
  5. Löcher für die Halterung bohren.
  6. Das PVC-Rohr auf 31,5cm ablängen und die Schnittkanten entgraten.
  7. Markierungen 1cm vom Rand setzen, sie stellen die maximal nutzbare Länge dar.
  8. Eine waagerechte Linie über die gesamte Länge einzeichnen, dies erleichtert später die Ausrichtung der Spulenhalter.

VI. Der Zusammenbau (grüne Zahlen)

  1. Einzelteile für Auslässe: nut_upscaled, screw_upscaled, Dichtring Innendurchmesser 15 mm, ca. 5cm PTFE Röhrchen (innen 2mm, außen 4mm)
  2. Eingebaute Auslässe
  3. Klebe die M4 Muttern mit Klebeband an die Halterung, das erleichtert die spätere Montage, die sonst sehr anstrengend wird. Achte darauf, die hintere Öffnung nicht zu verschließen.
  4. Schraube die M3 Schrauben in die Halterung
  5. So werden die Halterungen am PVC-Rohr befestigt, achte darauf, dass die oberen Löcher in einer Flucht mit den Kugellagern ist und die Schrauben festgezogen sind. Die Hintere Öffnung der Halterungen ist frei.
  6. Das ist der Zusammenbau, du kannst eine oder zwei zusammengesetzte "Spool_Holder" pro Spule nehmen. Ich nehme jeweils zwei, um ein Abkippen oder Verkanten der Spulen zu vermeiden.
  7. Die Silica-Box kann mit doppelseitigem Klebeband am Boden der Samla Box fixiert werden.
  8. Der Zwischenboden, Grid2mm, ist eingesetzt, Wasser kann nach unten abtropfen.
  9. Fülle Silica ein, entweder lose wie ich oder nutze kleine Beutel oder oder oder.
  10. Deckel drauf.
  11. Ordne die Spulen auf dem PVC-Rohr mit den Halterungen und Abstandhaltern, Spool_Guide, so an, dass sie sich leicht drehen lassen. Baue das Ganze ein.
  12. Die SilicaBox stört die Spulen nicht beim Drehen.
  13. Deckel drauf und samla_clips zum Abdichten anbringen.
  14. Hinstellen, freuen und benutzen.

title: Simplistic Bottle Crate Stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Well, some may say this is a stupid thing to share, but hey. If there is only one person who benefits from this, then it was worth it.

I have a compartment in my kitchen which holds exactly two crates of sinalco, coke, beer or whatever drink crates. Usually I simply stack the crates inside to build a "shelf" inside, but there is an issue with that.

Having crates stacked with the opening horizontal causes the bottles to fall out easily. Especially the empty ones tend to slide out and bounce loud on the floor, while you drag out a full one.

Before I used leftover furniture stands below the bottom crate to lift the front and keep them in place, but when moving the crated e.g. when replacing the upper crate the lower crate often slit down.

Well, you may say: Why using a 3D printer for this. Screw a wooden bock into the cabinet and you are done. Yes, that would have worked for you, but not in my case. I would not be able to insert/remove the upper crate anymore, as the space is limited. I also cannot use some kind of slide to move the boxed in and out, as there is a wooden frame behind the top of the door holding the workbench. So it must be removable.

However, this little holder fixes all issues for me and is a great helper. I remove it and can slide out the crates easily from storage. Afterwards I re-add the stand and the bottles stay where they are using gravity.

I printed in ABS as it was loaded and I am, lazy. PLA should work fine, too. I also used only one stand. There is no need to use two as the backside of the crates is completely on the ground, so the holder builds up a kind of a tripod where the back legs are one. It is quite stable. Also it works fine with two filled crates. If you want to use this for three or more crates you may want to use two stands or widen the stand using the included source file, as the lowest box needs to carry the weight of all bottles above and the bottom crates handle is bending already a little with just one crate sitting on it.

The triangle left outs are just a cheap way to spare plastic without making the part weak. This is just a five minute design with FreeCAD and writing this text took far longer than designing it. So do not blame me for the cheap design.

Happy Printing.

Votre imprimante dans un caisson, ne vous permet pas de bien visualiser ce qui se passe au niveau de l'extrudeur. Voici une solution pour palier à ce problème.
Un simple miroir et une tige de diamètre 8mm vous permettront d'avoir un visuel latéral sur votre extrudeur. Le support de miroir est pourvu d'un aimant, il est ainsi facile de le déplacer le long de la tige et de l'orienter. Il est possible de le plaquer contre la paroi du caisson lors de non utilisation. Installé sur une Anycubic I3 Mega.
Comme miroir j'ai pris celui-ci https://www.amazon.fr/gp/product/B000RZQI68
La tige est une tige de 8mm standard
L'aimant est de dimensions 20x5x1 mm
L'installation de l'aimant se fait en forçant un peu, il est bloqué et ne se déplace pas lors des mouvements verticaux, le miroir est sécurisé par une vis M3 16mm. Les fixations haute et basse de la tige peuvent être fixées soit par du scotch double face, soit par des vis M3.
(Les photos montrent le support de miroir avec 2 aimants sur le prototype, en fait un seul est suffisant et le déplacement vertical s'en trouve facilité)

Your printer in a box, does not allow you to visualize what is happening at the extruder. Here is a solution to overcome this problem.
A simple mirror and a rod of 8mm diameter will allow you to have a side visual on your extruder. The mirror holder is provided with a magnet, so it is easy to move it along the stem and orient it. It can be pressed against the wall of the box when not in use. Used on an Anycubic I3 Mega.
As a mirror I took this one https://www.amazon.fr/gp/product/B000RZQI68
The rod is a standard 8mm rod
The magnet is of dimensions 20x5x1 mm
The installation of the magnet is done by forcing a little, it is blocked and does not move during vertical movements, the mirror is secured by a screw M3 16mm. The upper and lower fixations of the stem can be fixed either by double-sided tape or by M3 screws.
(The photos show the mirror support with 2 magnets on the prototype, in fact only one is sufficient and the vertical movement is facilitated).

title: Light Diffuser Rig for IKEA Tertial Lamps

description.text:
This is a way of mounting a tracing paper to act as a light diffuser on the very common Ikea Tertial Lamps.

It's basically a 3 part model - upper part being the "Ring+Arc" with more "Arc" components glued on as needed. This is by designer in case there are some manufacturing dimensional variances in the lamps. Also to give a choice of how many mounting points you would like.

Thereafter, the other side is simply the "Ring". This is arrayed with magnets to clamp a tracing paper (or even colored cellophane paper of your choice) into the setup.

You will require ~5mm diameter X 3mm height magnets for this build. 12 to go around each "Ring" and 3 for each "Arc" component in your setup.

Have fun with this and hope to see some makes and photos with this Rig!

This item is made for correcting the feathers of 8mm Arrows with soft plastic feathers.
Note: ABS or something else heat resistant material needed, no PLA.

How to:

  • Print "part 1" 2pcs and "part 2" 3pcs
  • (Gluing them all together could be useful but is not necessary. If you want to, 2K glue might be good)
  • Connect all parts and put it over the feathers of the arrow as seen in the pictures
  • Get some hot water (80°C / 176°F)
  • Put the feathers with the corrector attached into the water for 5-10sec
  • Get it outside and move the corrector up and down a little bit (pls don't boil your hands)
  • Either wait for cooling down or get some cold water

Update notes:

description.text:
This is maybe the tiniest camera mount you will find on thingiverse. I was inspired by a couple other designs, but they did not hold the camera well.

So i redesigned the mount using solidworks from scratch.

It's made to hold the tiny aio camera's by the lens cup. I've tested the designs and they fit a 800VTL or VM275T camera. The camera angle is 10 degrees uptilt.

There are 3 models:
v3: A bit more sturdy. it will really 'grab' the camera, mount it as low as possible, and prevent rotation of the camera on impact. <--- Use this one. It's weighted at 0.29 grams.

v1: Use if you have a protective camera cover, the baseplate is thin and will break on impact.

v2 - Universal (Designed for E010/E011/JJRC H36/ Furibee F36) + thicker baseplate+small guiders for pcb alignment.

v2 - H8 - Specially designed mount for a Eachine H8 FC on a E010/E011 frame + thicker baseplate

The total weight of this pieces are:
0.20 grams for v1 - Universal

description.text:
I'll write more later, but this is a mod to pulsemedia's improved Y carriage, further reducing the crossbar's ability to rotate in Z (it shouldn't).

The top piece can be used alone with stock hardware, Adding the bottom piece will require replacing the 4 M5 axle bolts with M5x50mm bolts (you'll need 8 for both carriages) and a full set of spacers (4x eccentric nuts, which you can print, and washers/nuts to match the other spacer's height on the inside wheel axles). Everything can be printed or picked up at the local hardware store (even in the States).

One word of warning -- the hole positions have been adjusted, so the bottom plates are not compatible with Pulesmedia's top plates -- If you already have his, you'll have to reprint the set.

If you want to print the spacers, I've had good success with these, but metal ones are nicer ;)

  • install the lower plate tightening down all four together.
  • tighten the wheels to the rail
  • tighten the crossbar.
